18 SECTION 21. ORS 468.446 is amended to read:
19 468.446. (1) As used in this section:
20 (a) “Charge ahead rebate” means a rebate for the purchase or lease of a new or used light-duty
21 zero-emission vehicle or plug-in hybrid electric vehicle issued through the Charge Ahead Oregon
22 Program established under this section.
23 (b) “Low-income service provider” means an organization that provides health, dental, social,
24 financial, energy conservation or other assistive services to low or moderate income individuals or
25 low or moderate income households, as further defined by the Environmental Quality Commission
26 by rule.
27 (c) “Qualifying household” means a household with income that does not exceed 400 percent of
28 federal poverty guidelines.
29 (2) The Department of Environmental Quality shall establish a Charge Ahead Oregon Program
30 for providing charge ahead rebates to qualifying households and low-income service providers. The
31 Director of the Department of Environmental Quality may hire or contract with a third-party or-
32 ganization to implement and serve as the administrator of the program required by this section.
33 (3) The department may:
34 (a) Specify design features for the program; and
35 (b) Establish procedures to:
36 (A) Prioritize available moneys to specific income levels or geographic areas; and
37 (B) Limit the number of charge ahead rebates available.
38 (4) An eligible purchaser or lessee of a new or used light-duty zero-emission vehicle or plug-in
39 hybrid electric vehicle may apply for a charge ahead rebate for a portion of the purchase price or
40 may choose to assign the charge ahead rebate to a vehicle dealer or lessor.
41 (5) Rebates under the Charge Ahead Oregon Program shall be made from moneys credited to
42 or deposited in the Zero-Emission Incentive Fund established under ORS 468.449 or the Charge
43 Ahead Zero-Emission Incentive Fund established under ORS 468.447. A rebate may not be made un-
44 less there are sufficient moneys available to make the rebate.
45 (6) The department shall prescribe the rebate application procedure for eligible purchasers and
[10]

HB 4009
1 lessees. All rebate applications must include a declaration under penalty of perjury in the form re-
2 quired by ORCP 1 E.
3 (7) Charge ahead rebates shall be:
4 (a) Up to $7,500 for the purchase or lease of a new light-duty zero-emission vehicle or plug-in
5 hybrid electric vehicle, but not less than $2,500; or
6 (b) Up to $5,000 for the purchase or lease of a used light-duty zero-emission vehicle or plug-in
7 hybrid electric vehicle, but not less than $2,500.
8 (8)(a) To be eligible for a charge ahead rebate, a person requesting a rebate under the program
9 must:
10 [(a)] (A) Be a member of a qualifying household or be a low-income service provider.
11 [(b)] (B) Purchase or lease a new or used light-duty zero-emission vehicle or plug-in hybrid
12 electric vehicle. A lease must have a minimum term of 24 months.
13 [(c)] (C) Provide proof of an intent to use the light-duty zero-emission vehicle or plug-in hybrid
14 electric vehicle primarily on the public highways of this state, which may be satisfied by providing
15 proof of registration of the vehicle in Oregon.
16 [(d)] (D) Submit an application for a charge ahead rebate to the administrator of the program
17 within six months of the date of purchase or six months from the date the lease begins.
18 [(e)] (E) Retain registration of the light-duty zero-emission vehicle for a minimum of 24 consec-
19 utive months following the date of purchase or following the date the lease begins.
20 (b) An individual is not eligible for a charge ahead rebate if the individual, or a member
21 of the individual’s qualifying household, has received a rebate under this section on or after
22 the effective date of this 2026 Act.
23 (9) A person that receives a charge ahead rebate may not make or allow any modifications to
24 the vehicle’s emissions control systems, hardware, software calibrations or hybrid system.
25 (10)(a) If a charge ahead rebate recipient sells the vehicle or terminates the vehicle lease before
26 the end of 24 months, the charge ahead rebate recipient shall:
27 (A) Notify the administrator of the program of the sale or termination; and
28 (B) Reimburse the administrator for the rebate in a prorated amount based on the number of
29 months that the rebate recipient owned or leased the qualifying vehicle.
30 (b) The administrator may waive the reimbursement requirement under paragraph (a) of this
31 subsection if the administrator determines that a waiver is appropriate given unforeseeable or una-
32 voidable circumstances that gave rise to a need for the rebate recipient to sell the qualifying vehicle
33 or terminate the qualifying vehicle lease before the end of 24 months.
34 (11) Charge ahead rebate recipients may be requested to participate in ongoing research efforts.
35 (12) The administrator of the program shall work to ensure timely payment of charge ahead re-
36 bates with a goal of paying rebates within 60 days of receiving an application for a charge ahead
37 rebate.
38 (13) In establishing the Charge Ahead Oregon Program, the department shall provide opportu-
39 nities for public comment by qualifying households, low-income service providers and other
40 community-based organizations that are located in areas of this state that have elevated concen-
41 trations of air contaminants attributable to motor vehicle emissions, relative to other areas of the
42 state. The department shall use the comments received pursuant to this subsection to inform, eval-
43 uate and strengthen the design of the program in order to increase the usage of light-duty zero-
44 emission vehicles and plug-in hybrid electric vehicles.
45 (14) The administrator of the program shall, throughout the course of implementing the program,
[11]

HB 4009
1 conduct community outreach to qualifying households, low-income service providers and other
2 community-based organizations that are located in areas of this state that have elevated concen-
3 trations of air contaminants attributable to motor vehicle emissions, relative to other areas of the
4 state, in order to:
5 (a) Solicit feedback on program implementation; and
6 (b) Take steps to ensure that the program is promoted effectively.
7 (15) A vehicle dealer may advertise the Charge Ahead Oregon Program on the premises owned
8 or operated by the vehicle dealer. If no moneys are available from the program or the program
9 otherwise changes, a vehicle dealer who advertises the program may not be held liable for adver-
10 tising false or misleading information.
11 (16) A charge ahead rebate may not be combined with a rebate described in ORS 468.444.
12 (17) An organization that the department has hired or contracted with to implement and serve
13 as the administrator of the program may offer expanded financing mechanisms for program partic-
14 ipants, including, but not limited to, a loan or loan-loss reserve credit enhancement program to in-
15 crease consumer access to new or used light-duty zero-emission vehicles and plug-in hybrid electric
16 vehicles.
17 (18) The Environmental Quality Commission may adopt any rules necessary to carry out the
18 provisions of this section.
19 SECTION 22. No later than six months following the close of the third consecutive year
20 in which moneys available to the Charge Ahead Oregon Program established under ORS
21 468.446 are sufficient to provide a charge ahead rebate to each eligible person that applied for
22 a rebate under the program, the Department of Environmental Quality shall provide a report
23 to the committees or interim committees of the Legislative Assembly related to transporta-
24 tion, in the manner provided in ORS 192.245, that includes:
25 (1) A progress report on the Charge Ahead Oregon Program established under ORS
26 468.446;
27 (2) A recommendation on whether the moratorium on rebates provided under ORS
28 468.444 should be lifted; and
29 (3) A recommendation on whether the limit on charge ahead rebates imposed by the
30 amendments to ORS 468.446 by section 21 of this 2026 Act should be revised or repealed.
31 SECTION 23. This 2026 Act takes effect on the 91st day after the date on which the 2026
32 regular session of the Eighty-third Legislative Assembly adjourns sine die.
